00:37:57.340 --> 00:37:57.561
Hey.

00:37:57.561 --> 00:38:02.380
Very fun. Very good day.

00:38:02.380 --> 00:38:19.900
And we have auto-ball.

00:38:19.900 --> 00:38:24.990
Highlander leads the pack followed by Stanley and Sandstorm.

00:38:24.990 --> 00:38:27.780
And we have moving from Stanley.

00:38:27.780 --> 00:38:30.780
Ladies and gentlemen. The start of the DARPA Grand Challenge

00:38:30.780 --> 00:38:37.460
The cheering teams are now spectators.

00:38:37.460 --> 00:38:45.080
Their work is done. After months of tireless efforts, there's a lot at stake.

00:38:45.080 --> 00:38:45.523
And now Sandstorm.

00:38:45.523 --> 00:38:51.870
A vision they all shared will now be put to the test.

00:38:51.870 --> 00:38:57.380
You go.You go. You go.

00:38:57.380 --> 00:39:08.143
Highlander, Stanley, and Sandstorm.

00:39:10.143 --> 00:39:13.120
During the first eight miles of the race.

00:39:13.120 --> 00:39:20.544
Highlander gains two minutes on Stanley.

00:39:20.544 --> 00:39:23.610
At times, the Stanford robot

00:39:23.610 --> 00:39:31.583
seems confused and disoriented.

00:39:31.583 --> 00:39:39.490
Sandstorm is keeping pace with Stanley, five minutes behind.

00:39:39.490 --> 00:39:43.488
Launch of the sixth spot here. There. Are we there yet?

00:39:43.488 --> 00:39:52.390
It will take two hours to launch all the robots.

00:39:52.390 --> 00:39:55.040
Each one leaves the chute with confidence.

00:39:55.040 --> 00:39:58.715
A far cry from the first Grand Challenge with many faltering within sight

00:39:58.715 --> 00:40:04.255
of a start and no robot went beyond seven miles.

00:40:04.255 --> 00:40:05.820
The start of the race is pretty cool.

00:40:05.820 --> 00:40:09.775
It was really exciting to see all the robots go.

00:40:09.775 --> 00:40:11.525
I was excited and apprehensive.

00:40:11.525 --> 00:40:16.940
at the same time. You just don't know what's going to happen with a robot.

00:40:16.940 --> 00:40:21.630
It was entirely out of our hands.

00:40:21.630 --> 00:40:24.320
Far from the crowd,

00:40:24.320 --> 00:40:32.414
Highlander now leads a fleet of driver-less machine racing the clock across the desert.

00:40:32.414 --> 00:40:36.280
Team DAD has passed two robots,

00:40:36.280 --> 00:40:40.100
and is now heading to the front of the pack.

00:40:40.300 --> 00:40:47.934
Eight team robots have now passed the seven mile mark that ended the last race.

00:40:47.934 --> 00:40:54.595
Miraculously, the great team from New Orleans is holding its own,

00:40:54.595 --> 00:41:00.140
only weeks after the city was destroyed by hurricane Katrina.

00:41:00.140 --> 00:41:07.530
TerraMax was the last to start and brings up the rear.

00:41:07.780 --> 00:41:15.630
Following each robot, DARPA chase vehicles relay information back to the start.

00:41:15.630 --> 00:41:26.630
Here, teams gather around DARPA's displays.

00:41:27.680 --> 00:41:31.430
That's just pretty sweet. Throwing away in the front.

00:41:31.430 --> 00:41:31.438
For throwing.

00:41:31.438 --> 00:41:31.439
For now.

00:41:31.439 --> 00:41:34.670
We're pulling away from DAD.

00:41:34.670 --> 00:41:36.671
No, from Stanford.

00:41:37.070 --> 00:41:40.377
30 miles into the race,

00:41:40.377 --> 00:41:44.880
Highlander is making time on Stanley.

00:41:46.800 --> 00:41:54.863
Behind Stanley, Sandstorm is closing the gap and may pass the Stanford robot.

00:41:54.863 --> 00:42:01.150
behind them, robots are starting to drop like flies.

00:42:01.940 --> 00:42:08.481
At mile 26, team DAD's laser comes unbolted from the roof.

00:42:08.481 --> 00:42:11.790
Officials in the chase car hit the kill switch,

00:42:11.790 --> 00:42:13.545
and for the Hall brothers,

00:42:13.545 --> 00:42:17.039
the race is over.

00:42:17.039 --> 00:42:19.050
At a media stop,

00:42:19.050 --> 00:42:24.925
a group of journalists sees Highlander charging toward them in the distance.

00:42:24.925 --> 00:42:27.755
Highlander seemed to come down the hill very smartly.

00:42:27.755 --> 00:42:32.515
But then, as it started to mount the next hill,

00:42:32.515 --> 00:42:36.455
it looked like it ran out of gas,

00:42:36.455 --> 00:42:37.640
or the engine cut off,

00:42:37.640 --> 00:42:39.410
or somebody in there threw it into neutral.

00:42:39.410 --> 00:42:45.109
It just stopped moving and slid back down to the bottom of the hill.

00:42:45.109 --> 00:42:48.805
Something was wrong with Highlander,

00:42:48.805 --> 00:42:51.410
and it did not have its normal get up and go.

00:42:51.410 --> 00:43:00.411
Highlander keeps on rolling but cannot maintain its intended pace.

00:43:00.411 --> 00:43:07.485
Red and the team slowly realize that things are not going according to plan.

00:43:07.485 --> 00:43:10.329
I don't know whats going on with Highlander, it's weird.

00:43:10.329 --> 00:43:10.476
It's running slow.

00:43:10.476 --> 00:43:12.590
It's running real slow.

00:43:12.590 --> 00:43:24.500
Highlander struggles to summon the power to complete its mission.

00:43:33.800 --> 00:43:40.280
Behind it, Stanley is rapidly approaching.

00:43:46.870 --> 00:43:50.840
But Highlander recovers on the flats,

00:43:50.840 --> 00:43:55.860
and for many miles they continue neck and neck.

00:43:55.860 --> 00:44:06.055
One hundred and two miles into the race,

00:44:06.055 --> 00:44:11.750
Stanley's video camera records a milestone event.

00:44:21.750 --> 00:44:26.750
Stanley has passed Highlander.

00:44:38.790 --> 00:44:44.078
At that point, we pretty much knew Highlander wasn't going to win the race,

00:44:44.078 --> 00:44:46.505
we thought Sandstorm might have a chance.

00:44:46.505 --> 00:44:51.653
It was really disappointing.

00:44:51.653 --> 00:44:54.660
Five hours after leaving the starting line,

00:44:54.660 --> 00:45:00.015
Stanely now leads the pack and just five robots remain on the course.

00:45:00.015 --> 00:45:04.440
To finish, they must wind through a treacherous mountain pass

00:45:04.440 --> 00:45:10.040
and Stanley has now make life or death decisions.

00:45:14.720 --> 00:45:20.345
Somehow, Highlander has managed to reach the summit of the pass,

00:45:20.345 --> 00:45:24.395
but the gimbal is turned sideways and appears to be dead.

00:45:24.395 --> 00:45:26.740
Without its secret weapon,

00:45:26.740 --> 00:45:34.285
must rely on short range lasers and GPS to avoid disaster.

00:45:34.285 --> 00:45:43.000
Right behind Highlander, Sandstorm is in good shape but driving slowly according to plan.

00:45:54.570 --> 00:45:58.917
The crowd gathers.

00:45:58.917 --> 00:46:07.840
A blue dot appears in the distance.

00:46:07.840 --> 00:46:09.815
Yeah! Stanley!

00:46:09.815 --> 00:46:14.190
After driving six hours and 53 minutes,

00:46:14.190 --> 00:46:17.140
at an average speed of 90 miles an hour,

00:46:17.140 --> 00:46:21.420
Stanley is about to become the first vehicle in history to drive

00:46:21.420 --> 00:46:37.084
132 miles by itself.

00:46:43.084 --> 00:46:47.265
Bot 25. Red team, two.

00:46:47.265 --> 00:46:49.206
Highlander from this Pittsburgh PA,

00:46:49.206 --> 00:46:51.430
Carnegie Mellon University,

00:46:51.430 --> 00:46:54.175
the red team two is an alliance.

00:46:54.175 --> 00:46:56.190
21 minutes behind Stanley,

00:46:56.190 --> 00:46:59.800
Highlander limps to the finish.

00:47:06.080 --> 00:47:10.870
Minutes later, the trusty veteran appears

00:47:10.870 --> 00:47:37.430
Bot number19.

00:47:37.430 --> 00:47:43.895
It was just amazing to see this community of people.

00:47:43.895 --> 00:47:47.235
That community succeeded today.

00:47:47.235 --> 00:47:50.190
Behind me, there are three robots that made it all the way through

00:47:50.190 --> 00:47:53.575
the desert and all three of them did the unthinkable.

00:47:53.575 --> 00:47:56.450
It's such a fantastic success for this community.

00:47:56.450 --> 00:47:58.872
I think we all win.

00:47:58.872 --> 00:48:02.330
Before announcing the winner,

00:48:02.330 --> 00:48:06.460
DARPA officials honor the five finishing teams.

00:48:06.460 --> 00:48:10.346
TerraMax is fifth.

00:48:10.346 --> 00:48:12.840
A dark horse,

00:48:12.840 --> 00:48:15.291
the Gray Team from New Orleans, is fourth.

00:48:15.291 --> 00:48:21.683
Highlander is third.

00:48:21.683 --> 00:48:25.258
Sandstorm, Whittaker's tortoise,

00:48:25.258 --> 00:48:29.707
was just 11 minutes behind the winner.

00:48:29.707 --> 00:48:32.750
So, I guess it's time.

00:48:32.750 --> 00:48:38.150
The check goes to Stanley.

00:48:39.150 --> 00:48:44.150
So, someone from Stanley will please come up here.

00:48:44.150 --> 00:48:47.370
What Stanford did in

00:48:47.370 --> 00:48:53.255
a short span of time is amazing in the robotics world.

00:48:53.255 --> 00:48:57.640
On this scale of time to develop a system this sophisticated that can navigate

00:48:57.640 --> 00:49:02.179
so well over such a wide variety of terrain at such high speeds,

00:49:02.179 --> 00:49:06.640
it really is worth its place in the history books.

00:49:08.000 --> 00:49:12.280
The source of Highlander's problems remains

00:49:12.280 --> 00:49:16.443
a mystery that may have been the result of its rollover.

00:49:16.443 --> 00:49:20.205
The engine pump, the only thing that was

00:49:20.205 --> 00:49:24.720
short was not having a top end speed on the gas pedal.

00:49:24.720 --> 00:49:28.450
Except for that, ran like a charm.

00:49:28.450 --> 00:49:32.000
This really was like a horse race.

00:49:32.000 --> 00:49:35.765
It finished in such close times.

00:49:35.765 --> 00:49:45.065
So, the red team is justifiably proud for having both of its robots finished the course.

00:49:45.065 --> 00:49:49.440
Many believe the completion of the Grand Challenge is

00:49:49.440 --> 00:49:54.990
a giant step that will push robots out of the lab and into the real world.

00:49:54.990 --> 00:50:01.926
The forces that will make this happen are embodied in the passion and vision of true men.

00:50:01.926 --> 00:50:06.740
The world needs both Sebastian Thrun's and Red Whittaker's.

00:50:06.740 --> 00:50:11.210
If robotics is ever going to become part of the daily fabric of our lives,

00:50:11.210 --> 00:50:14.210
it needs those scientists who can come up with those far out

00:50:14.210 --> 00:50:17.869
ideas for how machines are actually going to start to think,

00:50:17.869 --> 00:50:24.045
to reason and it also needs the builders,

00:50:24.045 --> 00:50:29.185
the implementers, and those who are driven to make things work in the real world.

00:50:29.185 --> 00:50:32.830
There is every reason to believe all those who

00:50:32.830 --> 00:50:36.130
participated will continue their quest to innovate even

00:50:36.130 --> 00:50:43.116
though the Grand Challenge itself is now history.

00:50:43.116 --> 00:50:46.870
What about the future?

00:50:46.870 --> 00:50:53.170
Will mechanical warriors take over the battlefield?

00:50:53.170 --> 00:50:59.045
Will we all be passengers on the highways of tomorrow?

00:50:59.045 --> 00:51:05.710
Someday, the great robot race may well be remembered as a moment when

00:51:05.710 --> 00:51:13.510
the partnership between humans and the machines we create was forever changed.

